1. What the Two Tables Do

POM_UID_scratch2
	•	A temporary table used for the current session only.
	•	Holds a list of object UIDs specific to the user/session (e.g., selected/search result items).
	•	No persistent statistics — Oracle uses DYNAMIC_SAMPLING to estimate data size during each execution.
	•	Contains just one column, and is fully scanned during the query.

POM_M_LOCK
	•	Stores lock information for Teamcenter objects to avoid concurrent updates.
	•	Tracks which session/process holds a lock on which object.
	•	Important columns:
	•	REF_UID: ID of the locked object.
	•	PROCESS: The session/process holding the lock.
	•	ASPACE_UID: Identifies which revisioning “space” the lock applies to (e.g., private or public).

⸻

2. What the Query Is Doing

SELECT /*+ DYNAMIC_SAMPLING(tt 4) */ ref_uid, process
FROM POM_M_LOCK, POM_UID_scratch2 tt
WHERE ref_uid = tt.auid
  AND aspace_uid = 'AAAAAAAAAAAAAA'

Plain English:

“From my current session’s list of objects, tell me which ones are locked in the specified workspace (aspace_uid).”

	•	It joins session objects (POM_UID_scratch2) with lock data (POM_M_LOCK).
	•	It filters by a specific workspace context.
	•	It returns only the locked items from the session’s working list.

⸻

3. Dynamic Sampling – In Short
	•	Used when no stats are available, like with temporary or volatile tables.
	•	Oracle gathers sample data at query runtime to estimate row counts and costs.
	•	DYNAMIC_SAMPLING(tt 4) means Oracle samples 1/64 of the data from tt to guide its query plan.
	•	Helps avoid bad plans, but adds overhead to execution — especially for large data sets or high-concurrency environments.

⸻

4. Why the Query Is Slow (Based on Execution Plans)

Execution Varies – Oracle used 3 different plans:
	•	Hash Join with full scans
	•	Nested Loops with index access
	•	Different access paths on POM_M_LOCK

Key Performance Issues:

Cause	Impact
Dynamic Sampling	Adds overhead every time the query runs.
Temp Table Full Scan	Slows down with more session data.
Unstable Execution Plans	Different plans per session = unpredictable performance.
Inefficient Index Use	Index skip scans on POM_M_LOCK can be expensive.
Hash Join Memory Load	Hash join uses more memory — can spill to disk if overloaded.
High Concurrency	Many users running the same pattern cause CPU, memory, and I/O pressure.



