5. What Application Operations Could Trigger This

This type of query is likely triggered by user operations that involve session-level object lists, such as:
	•	Searching for objects across revisions or configurations
	•	Opening a large folder or structure (like BOM or assembly)
	•	Mass-selecting objects for operations (like revise, release, check-in/check-out)
	•	Performing bulk actions on objects shown in a Teamcenter workspace or result window
	•	Site-to-site transfer operations (multisite SSTs)

These operations load many object UIDs into the temporary table and then cross-check locks on them, leading to the query in question.

⸻

In Short:

The query is slow because it joins a session-level temporary table (with no fixed stats) to a lock table using dynamic sampling and varying execution plans. It’s especially expensive when many objects are involved or multiple users trigger it at once. Operations like searching, bulk actions, or workspace loading in Teamcenter are common causes.

